Document: RichTextLabel
Path: godot/classes/class_richtextlabel.rst
Summary: This chunk covers the main description and usage notes for the RichTextLabel node, which displays text with advanced formatting using a custom BBCode syntax.

Inherits: Control < CanvasItem < Node < Object

RichTextLabel is a control for displaying text. It's more advanced than Label, as it supports a custom BBCode for formatting. The supported tags are listed in the BBCode in RichTextLabel documentation.

Note: Unlike Label, RichTextLabel doesn't have a property to horizontally align text. Instead, alignment is controlled by BBCode tags such as `[center]` or `[right]`. For example, `[center]Hello world![/center]`.

Note: The default font is defined in the `font/normal_font` theme property. The default font color is defined in the `font/normal_font_color` theme property. These can be overridden on a case-by-case basis using BBCode.

Note: RichTextLabel uses a stack-based approach to formatting. Each formatting tag is pushed to a stack. The formatting is applied to the text after the tag. The formatting is removed when a corresponding closing tag is found. For example, `[b]bold[/b] normal` will display "bold" in bold and "normal" in the default font. It is not possible to supply an empty closing tag; the correct tag must be used to close a given tag.

Note: For the same reason, it is not possible to close a tag with a different tag. For example, `[b]bold [i]bold and italic[/b][/i]` is invalid. The correct way to write this is `[b]bold [i]bold and italic[/i][/b]`. This is because the `[/b]` tag will expect to close the most recently opened tag, which is `[i]`. Since it's not the correct closing tag, it will be ignored.

Note: Line wrapping will occur if the text is too long to fit. If you need to display a large amount of text, you may need to use a ScrollContainer to allow the user to scroll through the text.

Performance: RichTextLabel is slower than Label. If you don't need the features of RichTextLabel, use Label instead. If you are using RichTextLabel to display a large amount of text, you may experience performance issues. In this case, consider using a different approach, such as splitting the text into multiple RichTextLabel nodes or using a custom solution.
---CHUNK---
